          color="#000000"
        >
          <h2 style="font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.2; font-weight: 500">
            Bangladesh announces elections
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>
              Summary: On the first anniversary of the student uprising,
              Bangladesh announced election plans and recognized the protest.
            </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Bangladesh will
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-spotlight-h2-5-hold-its-first-elections?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >hold its first elections</a
            >
            since protests ousted former Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, with the
            vote set for February 2026, just before Ramadan. Interim leader
            Muhammad Yunus pledged to step down afterward, calling the vote the
            “final and most important phase” of the transition. He also unveiled
            the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-spotlight-h2-6-july-declaration?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >July Declaration</a
            >, which seeks constitutional recognition of the 2024 student-led
            uprising.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The anniversary:</strong> Bangladeshis gathered in Dhaka to
            mark the first anniversary of the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-spotlight-h2-7-mass-protest-movement?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >mass protest movement</a
            >. Yunus called for a democratic Bangladesh that promises the rule
            of law, moral values, and justice for victims of political violence.
            Leaders from major political parties joined Yunus, showing broad
            political support towards the declaration and election.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>The concerns:</strong> Yunus has struggled to deliver on
            some of his promises amid political turmoil and law and stability
            issues. Meanwhile, the ousted former PM Sheikh Hasina claimed she
            hadn’t resigned as the PM of the country and described the 2024
            student uprising as a coup.
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-6-aug-25-spotlight-h2-8-hasina-is-on-trial?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Hasina is on trial</a
            >
            in absentia in Bangladesh over crimes against humanity charges due
            to the deadly crackdown on the student protest.
          </p>
